Berdiri untuk Mendukung dan Menyebarkan Kebenaran

Dr. Cheng Cheng-bing berkata, “Pemutaran film ini sangat sukses. Luar biasa! Saya sangat terharu!” Ia mengacungkan jempol dan berkata, “Kami sangat berterima kasih kepada praktisi Falun Gong, The Epoch Times, Sound of Hope, dan media lain yang melaporkan hal ini. Kalian semua berdedikasi dan tidak mementingkan diri sendiri, sungguh luar biasa.”



Cheng Cheng Bing

Beliau berkata, “Kita semua harus belajar semangat ini, bangkit mendukung, dan memiliki keberanian untuk mengungkap kebenaran dan melawan PKT.”

Lebih Banyak Orang Harus Mendukung Film Ini

Setelah anggota Rotary Club, Tsai Han-lin menonton film tersebut, ia berkata, “Saya sangat tersentuh. Saya sangat mengagumi praktisi Falun Gong. Dulu, saya hanya mendengar bahwa mereka dianiaya, tetapi saya tidak tahu mengapa dan tidak dapat memahaminya. Sekarang, saya memahaminya dengan jelas.”



Anggota Rotary Club, Tsai Han-lin

Ia mengatakan bahwa setiap orang harus menjadi relawan untuk mempromosikan film ini, dan setiap orang di Taiwan harus menontonnya, “Meskipun kita tidak dapat menyelamatkan orang-orang yang teraniaya ini, kita harus menjadi relawan, mendukung, dan menyelamatkan mereka. Inilah yang harus kita lakukan.

“Film ini benar-benar dapat menyelamatkan Taiwan, praktisi Falun Gong, diri saya sendiri, anak-anak saya, keluarga, dan teman-teman saya. Saya akan memberi tahu lebih banyak orang tentang film ini. Semua orang harus mendukung film ini.”

Anggota audiens lainnya berkata, “Diskusi ini sukses dan informatif. Apa yang dibicarakan oleh beberapa profesor membantu memotivasi para mahasiswa muda dan anggota audiens untuk menjaga demokrasi, kebebasan, dan hak asasi manusia. Anak saya berkata kepada saya, 'Bu, kirimi saya situs web film State Organs. Saya akan menunjukkannya kepada teman-teman sekelas dan teman-teman saya yang tidak datang. Saya akan membagikannya di grup saya di Facebook sehingga lebih banyak orang dapat menontonnya. Ini sangat penting. Kita harus mengambil inisiatif untuk melindungi negara kita dan menjaga demokrasi, kebebasan, dan hak asasi manusia kita. Setiap orang memiliki tanggung jawab ini.'”

Yu Guan berkata, “Pemutaran dan diskusi berjalan dengan baik.” Ia berkata bahwa temannya membaca berita palsu di media luar negeri minggu lalu, tetapi setelah menonton film tersebut ia memahami kebenaran dan bertanya bagaimana cara belajar Falun Gong.

text:
Harga barang dari luar negeri di Amerika Serikat selain dari operasional impor dan harganya ditentukan melalui pelelangan  perusahaan Amerika Serikat terkait sebelum dipasarkan ke publik Amerika Serikat. Krus uang 1 Dollar Amerika adalah Rp.16.825.Harga tas tadi $ 38.000(Dollar Amerika Serikat) di Rp.639.350.000 harga sama dengan membeli rumah di Indonesia. kebijakan Amerika Serikat sekarang tidak pasti berpengaruh pada Krus Dollar akhirnya mempengaruh nilai mata uang negara yang menggunakan patokan Dollar Amerika Serikat.ini bagian dampak menggunakan patokan 1 krus uang negara. Apalagi mata uang ini bisa mengendalikan dan mengintimidasi perekonomian nasional negara yang menggunakan Dollar Amerika Serikat. Berbeda menggunakan patokan uang organisasi yang didasarkan pada rata rata keseluruhan PDB anggota organisasi dan transaksi keuangan pada kegiatan perekonomian di wilayah negara anggota organisasi.
Wing solution:
Menerapkan Dedollarisasi dengan mengadakan mata uang organisasi(mata uang BRICS) disertai mengadakan fasilitas mendukung kegiatan BRICS,seperti mengadakan jalur pelayaran dan penerbangan khusus negara anggota BRICS dilengkapi pengadaan pelabuhan dan bandara serta armada khusus BRICS. Adanya penerapan mata uang BRICS bagian dedollarisasi dari BRICS berdampak positif mengurangi ketergantungan menggunakan patokan krus Dollar yang berdampak mengurangi pengendalian dan intimidasi perekonomian nasional yang dilakukan oleh Amerika Serikat.

text:
As someone who has shopped  from China for a while now, there are 4 levels of 'fakes'. 

'水货' or '尾单' Grade OEM factory overproduction or made in the same factory with the same materials, by the same artisans from the original design blueprint of the designer brand. You need some local factory connections to get this.

Grade A These are produced with the same materials from the original design blueprint, but in another factory. 

Grade B These are produced using the closest materials available locally using the original design blueprint in another factory.

Grade C this is where a manufacturer completely unaffiliated with the original brand obtains an original item, takes it apart and tries to replicate it in their own factory using local materials with varying degrees of success. 

Make sure you are paying the right price point for the quality product you expect to get.

Happy shopping!

text:
As a Chinese person, this is practically an open secret. Due to the extremely fierce competition, China is capable of producing products at various quality tiers with price differences spanning hundreds of times to meet different market demands. OEM manufacturers working for international brands tend to maintain lower profiles - their relatively stable profit margins make them reluctant to publicize how much brands actually profit from their products, as this could strain client relationships. Were it not for Trump's maximum tariffs forcing brands to pressure manufacturers on pricing, these OEMs probably wouldn't have spoken out at all.

When purchasing, caution is essential. Contract manufacturers vary in scale and operate different production lines. The product grade you receive directly correlates with what you pay - similar appearances don't guarantee equivalent quality. Personal connections or trusted on-site inspections are strongly recommended.

The tragic reality is that many Chinese consumers insist on paying 10-20x premiums for "authentic" products, sometimes even for designs I consider objectively inferior, solely for that logo. If you prioritize quality over branding, approaching manufacturers directly makes perfect sense. China absolutely can produce world-class goods. Alternatively, consider manufacturers' in-house brands using identical production lines - slightly pricier than unbranded options, but matching OEM quality while often featuring superior designs in my observation.

text:
‌What Makes Luxury Goods Tick?‌
‌1. What Are They, Really?‌
Luxury items are ‌stuff you don’t need to survive‌ but desperately want. Their magic lies in walking a tightrope between ‌being super valuable‌ and ‌artificially rare‌. Think of it this way:
Economically, they’re priced sky-high compared to their actual usefulness (like a 10,000handbagthatholdsthesamestuffasa20 one).
The real value? ‌Brand hype‌ and ‌exclusivity‌—not practicality.
‌2. How Brands Play the Game‌
‌"Rarity" Scam‌: Brands jack up prices to make things feel rare. For example, Tiffany’s yellow diamond necklace jumped 59% in price—not because diamonds got pricier, but because they said it’s rare.
‌Capitalism’s Favorite Cash Machine‌: Modern luxury is all about mass production with a fancy story. They make millions of "limited edition" items but charge like they’re one-of-a-kind.
‌3. Social Superpowers‌
‌Classy ID Cards‌: Luxury goods are ‌VIP passes to the cool kids’ club‌. A Rolex watch or Hermès bag screams, "I’m rich/better than you." They’re tools to separate the "haves" from the "have-nots."
‌Power Flexing‌: Flaunting a Gucci belt or Chanel perfume isn’t just about style—it’s social shorthand for "I deserve respect (and better treatment)."
‌4. Why We Fall for It‌
‌Insecurity Band-Aid‌: Many buy luxury to patch up self-doubt. Big logos (like LV monograms) act as confidence boosters—"If I wear this, people won’t notice I’m faking it."
‌Selling Fairy Tales‌: Brands feed us stories about "centuries-old craftsmanship" or "royal heritage." They’re not selling products—they’re selling ‌daydreams of a fancier life‌.
‌5. The Big Debates‌
‌"But Is It Useful?"‌: True luxury used to mean irreplaceable quality (like ancient Chinese silk). Now? A $2,000 "limited" T-shirt falls apart after three washes—but the logo lasts forever.
‌"Culture or Con?"‌: Brands claim their goods carry "deep cultural meaning." Critics call BS—it’s just marketing to make you feel "unworthy" unless you pay up.
‌6. Modern Twists & Traps‌
‌Fake Democracy‌: Luxury brands now target the middle class ("Buy this $500 lipstick—you’re worth it!"). But they still pretend to be exclusive by releasing "drops" and "waitlists."
‌Sustainability Hypocrisy‌: They preach eco-friendly values but mass-produce in factories, clash with fair-trade ethics, and burn unsold stock to protect "exclusivity."
‌The Bottom Line‌
Luxury goods are ‌walking contradictions‌:
‌Money Makers‌: Overpriced status symbols that fuel capitalism.
‌Social Weapons‌: Tools to divide classes and flex power.
‌Emotional Cheat Codes‌: Quick fixes for insecurities and unfulfilled dreams.
‌Marketing Mirage‌: "Culture" and "craftsmanship" are often just smoke and mirrors.
‌The core recipe?‌
Make something feel rare (even if it’s not).
Mess with people’s heads to keep them paying.
In short: ‌Luxury isn’t about what you buy—it’s about how you’re tricked into wanting it.
